Jeremy Corbyn will make his debut on Prime Minister's Questions.
Since his election, Mr. Corbyn's debut at PMQ has been highly anticipated.
New Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn will make his debut on Prime Minister's Questions later, and for the first time will be working with David Cameron.
Mr Corbyn will ask the first of his six allotted questions shortly after noon, while his performance will likely be closely scrutinized by the media and MPs.
In his weekly statement, he called for "less drama and more facts".
He also stated that he might skip a few sessions, which he would leave to his colleagues.
This meeting will be the first parliamentary test of Mr Corby's leadership, coming after his appointment to the shadow cabinet and his speech to the annual TUC congress on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to stand in silence during the singing of the national anthem in the service on Tuesday to mark the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain has been met with criticism from a number of Conservative MPs and is the focus of several headline stories.
Mr. Corbin's decision not to sing the national anthem has attracted attention.
Mr. Corbyn's spokesman said he would "stand in respectful silence" and that he would recognize "the heroism of the Royal Air Force in the Battle of Britain".
However, a member of Mr Corbyn's shadow cabinet, Owen Smith, told BBC Two's Newsnight that he would recommend the Labour leader to sing the national anthem "regardless" of his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers refused to serve on Mr. Corbyn's top team, citing differences in the economy, defense and foreign affairs, and only less than a sixth of parliamentary parties originally supported him as leader.
BBC political correspondent Robin Brant says political differences at work are also "growing" after Mr Corbyn's appointment despite his position in the European Union and the government's benefit cap.
Mr. Corbyl told the TUC conference that the Labor Party had put forward amendments to remove the whole idea of the benefit limit.
Hours later, Mr Smith, the shadow secretary of state for work and pensions, said the party was "very clearly" opposed to the government's plans to reduce the limit from £26,000 to £23,000.
Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Labour leader to face David Cameron in the last decade since he was elected leader of the Conservatives.
The Labour leader, who has promised a different approach to politics, claims he has ideas "out of the crowd" for questions for Mr Cameron and has received more than 30,000 proposals.
MP Islington North claims that PMQs are too confrontational and that they abstain from both "ready answers" and "tooth-in-the-mouth" and instead promise to focus on important issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges faced by young people.
Mr Corbyn claims that Angela Eagle, the Shadow Trade Secretary, will represent him at PMQ when she's not attending - as, for example, when Mr Cameron travels abroad.
He also dropped the idea of letting other colleagues speak for him from time to time, as he was rumoured to have discussed the matter with Speaker of the House John Bercow.
When Mr. Cameron became leader in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the "Punch and Judy" style of politics that was often associated with the PMQ, but a few years later he admitted that he had failed.
Since its first broadcast in 1990, PMQs have been seen as a key barometer of leaders' judgement, their leadership of the House and their standing among other MPs, although critics have argued that they have become a caricature and need far-reaching reforms.
