Multiple sclerosis: it's not just the medication that matters, it's the patient's will to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complex disease, and a person diagnosed with it needs the care of a variety of specialists: neurologist, physiotherapist, occupational therapist, urologist, ophthalmologist, psychologist, psychiatrist, and many other specialists.
It is not just medical care, however, for example, that women with MS need to be consulted if they decide to have a child, and care for these patients includes social legal advice, advice on housing adjustments, etc.
However, this is not enough: the course of the disease can be influenced in a major way by the patient.
The more actively he fights the disease, the longer he can work and the more he does not have to make fundamental changes in his lifestyle.
As doctors point out, the passivity of the sick leaves room for the activity of the disease.
For example, regular exercise has been shown to significantly delay the time when a sufferer needs a compensatory aid, such as a cane.
It's important that patients and those around them don't fall prey to myths, such as that the disease automatically leads to a wheelchair.
This is why the Give Yourself a Chance website (www.bezmytu.cz) was created, which is supported by the ongoing Give Yourself a Chance media campaign.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
In multiple sclerosis, the earlier the disease is treated, the more likely the doctor is to have an influence.
It's because we have drugs for MS in the inflammatory stage, when the neurodegeneration process is not yet so strong.
The sooner we intervene, the better the chance we have of stopping the disease and delaying disability, explains Dr Eva Medová, from the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
Rehabilitation care is very important for people with MS, which most often addresses weakness in the lower limbs or balance disorders.
Patients are treated according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, to improve gait, to strengthen the pelvic floor, to reduce swallowing disorders, or to improve coordination.
"It's really individual, it depends on the specific problems of the patient", says Dr. Martina Kövári, head of the Clinic of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine of the Faculty Hospital in Motolä.
People with MS suffer from the same disease, but the symptoms vary slightly.
Rehabilitation can't stop the disease, but it can always relieve its symptoms.
However, physical activity also strengthens the body's immune system, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another benefit of regular exercise is that it helps patients to see what they can do, and it builds their self-confidence.
"Exercise also releases endorphins and makes you feel good", notes Dr. Kamla Rassova of the Rehabilitation Clinic at the Royal Vinohrady University Hospital.
By affecting the physical side, we affect the limbic system responsible for emotions.
We're directly intervening in the psyche and the immune system, stabilizing the disease, he says.
"In the past, these patients were so-called 'saved', but now we know that they need a targeted load", says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, head of the Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine Clinic at the University Hospital in Motola.
The goal of physical therapy is to help you remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including employment.
Physical therapists therefore work with occupational therapists to provide each person with a compensatory device tailored to his or her needs.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or a psychiatrist.
They're in a tough situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, most people are shocked.
They're going through shock, panic, fear.
They must respond to the great burden of health loss.
With a soul this sick, we should go to someone, not try to carry everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them to reach the conclusion that disability is not the end of life, and that MS is not the end of life", says psychotherapist Renata Malinová-Schubertová of the Neurological Clinic of the Faculty of General Medicine in Prague.
