Sonogenetics, or the manipulation of brain cells by sound waves
This video shows how sound impulses affect the direction of the hedgehog's movement.
Scientists have bred worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can control sound waves.
Tiny spines change direction when they are hit by sound impulses that are inaudible to the human ear.
The pulses work by switching the cells of genetically engineered motor neurons that are programmed to respond to these ultrasonic waves.
Related: Scientists can read and record brain activity using light
Scientists say that these worms are a fine example of a new technique called sonogenetics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart, and muscle cells and activate outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that the method could one day replace deep brain stimulation - an invasive procedure in which electrodes are injected into a patient's brain to stimulate the brain, a method used to treat symptoms of Parkinson's disease, for example.
The ticks do not normally respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they did when placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found that the bubbles amplified the ultrasonic waves that then passed through the worms' bodies.
The amplified ultrasound waves are produced in the TRP-4 ion channels found in the membranes of some worm cells.
The sound waves open these channels and activate the cells with which they are connected, reports the journal Nature Communications.
To control the worms with ultrasound waves, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons contained TRP-4 ion channels.
When he then applied ultrasound to the worms, the sound waves were amplified by the microbubbles and transmitted to the worms, where the modified motor neurons were activated.
The new method is similar in many ways to optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light.
But Chalasani suggested that sonogenetics could have many advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent through an optical fiber to a desired location in the brain, ultrasound waves can penetrate tissue without restriction and be sent directly to the brain.
"We believe that by using gene therapy and therapeutic viruses, we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to the ultrasonic signals used in clinical treatment to treat neurological diseases", Chalasani said.
He added that the method could also be used to treat muscle cells and insulin-producing cells.
