The wheel of the windmill over Chlum is turning again after years.
It is visible from afar, as it is placed on a 50-foot-high [50 m] pole.
People from the outskirts call it "the windmill on the Chlum".
For the village of 150 inhabitants, it even became one of the elements of the village coat of arms, which the village acquired on the occasion of the 2010 gathering of locals.
"We asked for a sign and of course we wanted to have a fan on the sign, everyone in the area knows it", stated Mayor Jiří Mašek.
The Chlumsky wind pump is a local engineering monument.
It's a bit of a modern-day reminder of a time when the people here were fighting for safe drinking water.
In the past, it was a rare commodity in Chlum.
It was not until 1910 that the Chlumsk representatives decided on a solution, which was then accepted until the mid-1980s.
In the village near the Chichov River, they had a well dug seven meters deep.
Three years later, a metal structure with a wind pump was added to the well, which pumped water to a reservoir at the highest point of the village, near the local church.
"The construction was carried out by Antonín Kunc from Hranic na Moravě at a cost of 2,400 CZK", says the memorial inscription on the ground floor of the mast structure.
The engine was repaired several times and the windmill was taken down in 1971.
On May 7, 1973, a new chapter in the struggle for water began: a new water supply system was put into operation in Chlum.
The wind pump was no longer more than a nonfunctioning commonplace symbol and a local rarity.
The Dominant was activated at this year's Native American gathering.
It was not until 2008 that the Chlumskys decided to repair the windmill and restart it.
They had a replica made of the original wheel - reduced by half a meter in diameter.
The wheel was mounted on a pole, but it had to be lowered that same year.
The replica's manufacturer had not selected the right material, and the wheel was not designed to withstand gusts of wind.
Then the slum dominanta rested for several years under a roof, dismembered.
But since June of this year, the wheel has been spinning again on the high mast.
For the occasion of the native gathering, the community had the replica wheel modified and re-installed it on top of the iron tower.
But the wheel only pumps the water from the well into the blind arm of the overpass.
And we turned it off completely for the summer because the well was low on water.
At least it was empty.
"In the autumn, the shafts of the wind wheel from the pump in the bag are disconnected again", explained Mayor Mašek.
Chlum is not the only municipality in the Czech Republic where the windmill has become a municipal symbol, but it is the only one of its kind in the entire Highlands.
