In their most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve lawmakers will spend two days this week sitting at a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table deciding whether, after nearly a decade, it's time to raise the key interest rate.
Overhead at one end of the central bank's ornament, the two-story boardroom will be a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are to put the nation's economic interests above all else.
The Fed has a dual charge from Congress: to maximize American employment and to keep American prices stable.
But since the Great Recession, Fed officials have recognized that there is an unwritten third term: financial stability.
And this third term could be the X-factor in too close to the predictable decision to be announced on Thursday as to whether the US economy is ready to bootstrap from the unprecedented stimulus of near-zero short-term interest rates in place since late 2008.
Although most data shows solid economic growth, the recent turbulence in global financial markets could scare the already cautious Fed into adding to the volatility by raising its federal funds rate of reference - by no more than a mere quarter of a percentage point.
"It's clear that the labour market and inflation will be the first and foremost thing to watch", said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at the brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think they were just looking for an excuse not to raise the rate, the increased uncertainty surrounding the global market already provides them with enough justification to wait", she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is a cause of nervousness in the financial markets.
About half of the economists recently polled by Blomberg expected a rate hike this week.
But financial markets expect the Fed to delay the issue, with a key indicator only about a 30% chance of an increase.
This would indicate a stock market decline in the event that the Fed raises rates, only if politicians soften the decline by promising that another increase is in the offing.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The rally was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers would hold rates this week, according to John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be a surprise if the Fed were to raise rates now", he says.
If Fed policymakers did so, "they would have to go to extremes in their policy statements and hold the financial markets by the hand so that they do not panic".
Other experts argued that raising rates would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, it seemed that the Fed was well on track to raise rates by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US economic recovery.
Yellen said she expects rates to rise this spring and early summer despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the labour market has shown solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate dropped to 5.1% the previous month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to what the Fed considers full employment.
Wage earnings have shown signs of rising.
And while inflation continues to be below the central bank's 2% annual target, Fed policymakers say the main reason has been the temporary effect of the sharply lower oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tightness of the labour market", said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to rally late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell as much as 16% below its record high in May as investors feared that a slowing Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market has bounced back somewhat this month and the Dow is now down almost 10% from its May high.
The Fed's policy makers are given a complex calculation by the volatile market situation as to when to take an interest rate hike.
"In the absence of what's happened in the financial markets, and the reports of the weakness of the Chinese economy in the last few weeks, there would have been a tightening at this meeting", said Stephen D. Oliner, senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now he predicts they'll wait at least a month to gain better control of the consequences.
