For moderately obese diabetics, weight loss surgery may be helpful
The benefits of weight-loss surgery for moderately obese people with type 2 diabetes can last for at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is too early to say whether moderately obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight-loss surgery than those given nonsurgical treatment.
"The mortality reports take a long time to display", claims Dr. Robin Blackstone, a weight loss surgery expert who wrote the introduction to a new JAMA surgery study.
Weight loss surgery, bariatric surgery, they use different methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
Reducing hunger and limiting the human body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective for the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most of the research has been done in people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
A BMI that measures a weight-to-height ratio is considered normal between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or more indicates overweight, and people with a BMI of over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected from a 2007 study that involved two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastrektomy - in treatment procedures for type 3 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The average BMI among those who had the surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of their fifth year, according to the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who did not receive surgical treatment for diabetes remained about the same at 29.
Among the patients who had surgery, 36 percent had their diabetes completely resolved and 28 percent had it partially resolved.
In the treatment group, diabetes was completely resolved in only 1% of patients and partially resolved in only about 2% of patients for comparison.
Also, control of blood pressure, triglycerides, and "bad" LDL cholesterol was shown to be "generally better in the surgical group", the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient' s blood levels of haemoglobin A1c, which reflects the body' s ongoing blood sugar level.
The best way to keep hemoglobin A1c below 7 percent, say researchers.
After the operation, the average hemoglobin A1c dropped from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
However, in the treatment group, this value remained at about 8%.
But this better "glycemic control" - reflected in better hemoglobin A1c levels - did not reduce mortality over five years, according to the lead researcher, Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu, and his colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results of the two types of operations.
After five years, the bypass group lost more weight compared with the gastrectomy group (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), had greater decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent versus 2.1 percent), and were more likely to have diabetes remission (46.9 versus 16.7 percent).
While the new study does not show an improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of heavier people in Sweden, where they found that surgery leads to an extension of life, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College of Medicine-Phoenix.
According to a Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery had about a 29 percent better chance of surviving the next 15 years, compared with the group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not show an improvement in survival among patients after surgery, Blackstone said it's a reassuring result for people with BMIs under 35 who are interested in these procedures.
"This is where this work is critical, because it shows that surgery is safer in the lower BMI group", without an increased risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
Blackstone also argues that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously once a patient's BMI falls between 27 and 30.
"I think we've waited too long to make people aware of the seriousness of the situation", he says.
