FriendsFest: a comedy show that teaches us a serious lesson about male friendship
The absence of similar depictions in various shows is striking, especially given the need for men to open up more desperately than ever before regarding suicide among young men under 15.
In 2013, it was the single biggest cause of death in men aged 20-45 in the UK and remains three times more common in men than in women.
In an effort to address this issue, the Campaign Against Living Miserably (CALM) designated 2015 as the Year of the Man, with the aim of challenging the culture that prevents men from seeking help when they need it.
At the heart of this struggle is a friendship to meet this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2,000 high school students who were showing symptoms of depression found that if the depressed person had a high enough percentage of "good-humoured" friends, their chances of recovery doubled.
Similarly, for those who are not depressed, having a circle of mentally healthy friends is half the chance of having mental health problems.
But of course, for friendships to work, they must first be attainable.
In this social media communication with an emphasis on style over content, instant response is often preferred over meaningful contact.
Our digital lives have doubled down on our need to appear stronger, more fun loving and more successful, even though we're more isolated in reality.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call external values; money, image, social status, all at the expense of our true values -- our personal desire for growth and friendship -- which have a profound effect on our mental health.
And as a billionaire and game designer recently explained, money really doesn't buy more happiness.
The beauty of Friends was the source of his idea.
None of the characters were defined by their work, but by their personalities, which shone through friendly interaction.
Joey's humor and Chandler's frequent sacrifices, the moments of watching football on the armchairs, Ross' desire for Rachel, all stem from the realization that, yes, men can identify with that too, even if they mostly keep their feelings to themselves.
As one Samaritan worker explained to me, "...my role as a listener of people who feel depressed or have suicidal tendencies has really confirmed to me that even the smallest friendly interactions can make a difference".
Men who contact us often feel unable to communicate with their friends.
The old adage "deal with it" is strong in the sense that it will be perceived as weak to open up about the problems.
Friends is one of the shows that pops into my head when I'm trying to offer a longer-term settlement mechanism.
It highlights the small moments in male friendship.
As far as my task is concerned, being an outsider on the phone helps people in times of despair, but long-term support has to come from a closer place, from a network of friends and family.
So if you're going to FrendsFest this weekend on Comedy Central, why not take your friends out for a drink in Central Park, where the interior will be completely redesigned for the occasion.
Or if you see someone alone at Starbucks, smile at them and say hello.
You never know what a difference your friendship can make.
