How the refugee crisis has shattered the Schengen area.
Far from reassuring the European crew, the German-fired emergency beacon is already forcing the ship to change course, reports the French daily Le Figaro.
The European Union decided on Monday to tackle the refugee problem head-on: it will systematically sort migrants and asylum seekers as they enter the old continent - especially Greece - rather than fight over future distribution of refugees by quota on the basis of a quantity that is increasingly distant from reality.
Six days after European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker asked 25 of the 28 EU countries to relocate 160,000 refugees, the EU's interior ministers have shifted their priorities.
Before dealing with the final destination of refugees, we must first filter those who are already arriving and decide the fate of those who are already moving within the Schengen area.
'An effective management of the EU's external borders is essential for managing migration', underlines the text discussed by ministers in Brussels on Monday.
After the crisis of the single currency, the EU finds itself at risk of its next big integration project.
Germany may be surprised, but it does not lose its resolve and increases the pressure.
It re-establishes border controls, especially with Austria, but without blocking the flow of those seeking asylum in that country.
The central power is making it clear that without it, no free movement in Europe is possible.
The fact that Austria and Slovakia joined the measure on Monday already served as proof.
Poland, the Netherlands, Belgium and even France are also considering it, albeit with varying degrees of intensity.
Hungary has already made progress.
These exceptional and temporary measures are permissible under the Schengen rules.
It's a domino effect, but it's also a blind man's view.
The key issue for Berlin and Paris is now the effective introduction of mandatory entry checks in Greece, southern Italy and also in Hungary for those who have already crossed into the interior.
French Interior Minister Bernard Cazeneuve and his German counterpart Thomas de Maizière discussed the issue intensively in a private meeting with their three Greek, Italian and Hungarian counterparts.
This idea is not new, but it is being implemented.
In Italy, according to unofficial statistics, two thirds of newly arrived refugees have already been registered and identified by fingerprinting.
Budapest refuses to establish any entry point on its territory, because it fears more than others that there will be no camps on its shoulders, where refugees will gather at its expense.
The real black hole is Greece.
More than 200,000 people have landed on its islands off the coast of Turkey this year, twice as many as have arrived in Italy recently.
Most of them are genuine asylum seekers who came directly from Syria after passing through overcrowded camps in Lebanon, Turkey and Jordan.
It's a giant, yawning hole.
Athens, still in financial turmoil and waiting for a new government, has folded its hands.
This is the starting point for the Balkan journey and the source of common concerns for German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orbán.
The Juncker Commission promises to implement the checkpoints as soon as possible, but has not given a number or a date.
'The challenges facing Greece are common to all of Europe', EU interior ministers agreed on Monday to mobilise on this front.
The idea is to deploy the intervention teams of the European Agency for the Control of Frontex in this country.
The EU wants to help Greece to expand its capacity to receive asylum seekers and to strengthen surveillance of the islands.
"Adequate financial resources will be required", warns the text submitted to ministers for approval.
In law, Athens will continue to have the final say.
The question of creating a real European border guard has not been formally raised, but Europe is getting close.
The new emergency situation of 28 has, however, put to the side the issue of binding quotas and 160,000 refugees, which was raised at the beginning of the year by the Juncker Commission and the European Parliament and strongly supported by Angela Merkel and French President François Hollande.
Hungary, Slovakia, the Czech Republic and Poland still refuse to hear about it.
They see it as an attack on their sovereignty.
The number, but not the obligation, was retained in the text approved by a majority of 28 on Monday.
But as a political commitment.
In other words, the process is interrupted.
The only firm commitment is the relocation of 40,000 refugees over the next two years, which was already agreed at the hectic EU summit in June, Le Figaro writes.
