In the event of CK's bankruptcy, insurance companies are to pay the full amount of the claims of their clients.
Insurance companies should pay the clients' claims in full in the event of the travel agency's bankruptcy.
The House decided on Wednesday when it passed the amended law on the conditions of business in tourism.
Travel agencies will be able to substitute bank guarantee for bankruptcy insurance under the bill that's going to the Senate.
Insurance companies are not happy with the obligation to pay claims beyond the agreed limit.
The Ministry of Local Development is insisting on the amendment, arguing consumer protection.
Insurance companies have already threatened to end travel agency bankruptcy insurance if the bill is paid.
But the proposal has also been criticized by travel agencies.
Without insurance, they'll have to quit or go abroad.
The Minister for Local Development, Karla Šlechtová (ANO), pointed out that cases where insurance companies did not pay full compensation were not Eurocompliant.
She pointed to a decision by the Constitutional Court this year, which confirmed that the client is entitled to a full refund regardless of the insurance limit.
The Commission will continue to monitor the situation and will continue to monitor the implementation of the new rules.
"We appreciate the effort to increase consumer protection, but it has to be limited in order to be feasible", opposed TOP 09 Vice-President Miroslav Kalousek.
He says the bank guarantee won't work because nobody gives it indefinitely.
"Travel agencies will have to close or move abroad", Kalousek warned.
Member of the board of the Association of Czech Travel Agencies and Agencies Tomio Okamura (SPD) disagreed with Kalouskov's concerns based on a survey among CK members.
"Stop showing us lobbying insurance companies", he said.
Okamura does not consider the statements of the insurance companies to be relevant, as according to him there is no official written statements of the insurance companies in this respect.
They're checking to see if the travel agencies are complicit, which Okamura says is fine.
Jana Fischer (ODS), who referred to the opinion of the competing Association of Czech Travel Agents, and her party colleague Petr Bendl, who spoke about the erasing of stairs by Czech travel agencies, also warned against the provision.
Travel agents, according to Fischer, won't be able to negotiate insurance.
"Consumer protection is working", Fischer said.
Her motion to have the controversial passage removed was not passed by the House.
Neither did Vojtěch Filip (KSČM) with the proposal to return the proposal to the committee due to the alleged contradiction with the Civil Code.
Philip warned of travel agencies that he believed could endanger consumers.
The rapporteur for the preliminary draft, Martina Berdychová (ANO), withdrew her proposal, which would have limited the liability of insurance companies in cases where they could not know that the insurance coverage did not cover the entire risk, in view of the ruling of the Constitutional Court.
The amendment will not introduce the originally proposed minimum insurance limit of 4 million for travel agencies offering air travel and the limit of 1 million for agencies selling, for example, bus trips.
The threshold remains at 30% of the planned sales of the tours.
However, the limit of the insurance cover will have to be such as to cover all the claims of the customers in the event of the travel agency's bankruptcy.
The revised standard provides that travel agencies will have to re-indicate which tour agency is organising the tour on the sold tours.
Travel agencies will have to provide insurance companies with, among other things, data on the organisation and number of trips before the contract is concluded.
The amendment adopted by the Public Administration Committee also provides for further regular information to be given to insurance companies.
Travel agencies will have to provide them with monthly data on the number of passengers and the number of trips sold, the total price of the trips sold and the amount of the advance payments and sales of the trips and the tickets.
If the Ministry of Local Development finds that the travel agency has not fulfilled any of its legal obligations towards the insurance company, it will either expel it according to the draft to rectify or it will be able to prohibit it from concluding new contracts if the breach of the obligation could endanger the interests of customers.
The amendment also aims to reorganise the financing of the mountain service.
The Ministry of Local Development will determine the amount of the grant to the mountain service on the basis of its application, which will be submitted by the end of April of each year for the following year.
The request will include a report on the use of public funds in the last year, a financial plan of expenditure and a forecast for the next two years.
According to the association, the legislator did not consider the situation that would arise if the insurance company terminated the CK contract.
She's not allowed to run the tour, and clients who bought the tour before the insurance was cancelled are going to lose it, according to the association.
In such a case, the CK would suffer a significant loss and might even go bankrupt, despite the fact that its management was in good shape.
One way in which travel agencies can deal with this situation is to sue the State for compensation.
Another option would be to go abroad and use the much softer conditions abroad and then we will only act as agencies in our market, said the vice president of the association Jan Papež.
The draft amendment also includes the institution of a bank guarantee, but it is so ill-conceived that it cannot be implemented in practice, as a bank guarantee cannot be set at an unlimited amount.
Moreover, the association considers that the change in the current practice is de facto unnecessary.
In the next two years, the whole law will have to be revised again due to the new EU directive.
The Czech Republic has a total of 942 active insured travel agencies.
Only three CIs have ceased their activities this year.
Domestic travel agencies sell about $25 billion worth of trips annually.
