Xi calls for opening up the economy to the wider world
It is necessary to open the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told a group tasked with reforming governance on Tuesday.
"China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improve open-ended policies", he said of the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group for Deepening Comprehensive Reform.
The promotion of opening up in the nascent reforms will add new impetus and vitality, as well as provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Leadership Group adopted a number of directives, including a negative list regulatory market access, liberalization of border control policy, encouraging state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to absorb private capital and reorganization of the registration system.
The Declaration states that a negative list will be drawn up identifying sectors and enterprises that are outside the investment thresholds.
This system will be tested and improved gradually through pilot programmes.
The move is significant because it will give the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensure a legal business environment and make the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also loosen controls on the powers it delegates to companies, and make sure that companies themselves decide how to run their businesses.
The declaration also states that China will enable cross-border areas to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to support regional growth.
In an effort to open up the state-controlled sector, more areas will be opened up to private investment.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of companies that are funded from abroad and provide them with better services", the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a 'green card' by optimising the requirements and simplifying the application process.
The meeting also discussed the issue of ensuring lawyers' rights to practice and developing professional judges and prosecutors.
The meeting was also attended by Premier Li Keqiang and senior officials Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
